{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584943"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:00:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:00:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14836"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14836"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.2,0.67,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"7880"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"},{"type":"tags","id":"10726"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18548"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHaemophilia B (Christmas disease) is an X-linked recessive bleeding disorder characterised by spontaneous bleeding and prolonged bleeding after injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following coagulation factors is deficient in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor V","Factor VIII","Factor IX","Factor X","Factor XI"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHaemophilia B is primarily caused by genetic mutations in the factor IX gene located on the X chromosome, making it more common in men. Family history is a significant risk factor, as the disorder is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern. Haemophilia B is caused by a deficiency in \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor IX\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemophilia A (deficiency of \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VIII\u003C/strong\u003E) is more common than haemophilia B however both present with an increased risk of bleeding events. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor X\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor XI\u003C/strong\u003E deficiencies cause other rare bleeding disorders but are not associated with classical haemophilia. Factor IX functions in the intrinsic coagulation pathway by forming a complex with activated Factor VIII to activate Factor X, ultimately leading to clot formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis can be confirmed by finding a prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT) with a normal prothrombin time (PT), followed by specific factor assays showing reduced Factor IX levels. Both are treated with replacement therapy using either factor VIII (for hemophilia A) or factor IX (for hemophilia B).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemophilia B (Christmas disease) is caused by deficiency of coagulation factor IX.","Factor IX is part of the intrinsic coagulation pathway and activates factor X alongside factor VIIIa."],"references":["Kitchens, C. S., Konkle, B. A., \u0026 Kessler, C. M. (2013). Consultative Hemostasis and Thrombosis: Expert Consult-Online and Print. Elsevier Health Sciences","Alshaikhli A, Killeen RB, Rokkam VR. Hemophilia B. [Updated 2023 Oct 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560792/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T10:43:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T10:43:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes